jq. In ruby that‚Äôs very trivial, it‚Äôs just about using the group_by method like that:
[
  {name: "John", age: 35},
  {name: "Bob", age: 40},
  {name: "Wally", age: 35}
].group_by{|u| u[:age]}

# {
#   35=>[{:name=>"John", :age=>35}, {:name=>"Wally", :age=>35}],
#   40=>[{:name=>"Bob", :age=>40}]
# }

But using jq I had to break it down to a few steps. So let‚Äôs say that I have this json:
[
  {"name": "John", "age": 35},
  {"name": "Bob", "age": 40},
  {"name": "Wally", "age": 35}
]

The idea is that we‚Äôll call the group_by(.age)[] function to return multiple groups, then I pipe it to create a map with the age as the key. Finally we‚Äôll have these bunch of nodes not surounded by an array yet, so I am pipeing to a new jq command to add with slurp:
cat data.json |
  jq 'group_by(.age)[] | {(.[0].age | tostring): [.[] | .]}' |
  jq -s add;

# {
#   "35": [{"name": "John", "age": 35},{"name": "Wally", "age": 35}],
#   "40": [{"name": "Bob", "age": 40}]
# }

default value when getting a node in json using jq:
{
  "users": [
    {"name": "John"},
    {}
  ]
}
cat my.json | jq '[.users[] | .name // "my-default"]'
# [
#   "John",
#   "my-default"
# ]

try/catch are not guaranteed to be an instance of Error class, or a child of Error . The exception caught can be anything - an object of any type, string, number, null‚Ä¶ you name it.

So in typescript, the compiler won‚Äôt like: 
try {
  //...
} catch(e) {
  console.log(e.message); // => Compiler will error with `Object is of type 'unknown`
}


The typescript compiler can‚Äôt infer the type of e, so defaults the type to unknown. If you know your error will have a message,  you can do something like this:
try {
  //...
} catch(e) {
  const error = e as { message: string };
  console.log(error.message);
}

null or all to the limit clause effectively ignores the limit clause. 
-- both statements return all user emails
select email from users limit null;
select email from users limit all;
